  {
    "plataforma": "tiktok",
    "idioma_nativo": "en",
    "external_id": "7592366548732431623",
    "username": "nadiaaddesi",
    "nombre": "Nadia Addesi",
    "seguidores": 2800000,
    "bio": "Registered social worker & psychotherapist 🇨🇦 \nNadia@evolveandbloom.com",
    "descripcion": "Disclaimer - This framework applies to relationships where both partners are emotionally safe and acting in good faith. It does not apply to abuse, intimidation, coercion, or chronic disrespect. And it only works when both people are willing to reflect and make changes.\n\nAs a couples therapist, this is one of the most common dynamics I see.\n\nOne person is trying to change the relationship forward. The other is trying to keep things calm. Both make sense. Both are usually coming from love.\n\nThe problem is the loop it creates. One partner starts pushing harder because they feel alone in the effort. The other starts shutting down because they feel like they can’t win. Then both people start reacting from stress instead of actually hearing each other.\n\nWhen you understand it as two nervous systems trying to feel safe, it gets easier to stop making each other the enemy. And it becomes easier to build a middle that works for both of you.\n\nIb: Dr Alexandra Solomon & @bayavoce",
